<br>
First off the official English site just launched so let me drop that here for those interested, and then on to your questions.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.playonline.com/ff11us/index.shtml" target="top">www.playonline.com/ff11us/index.shtml</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>For starters, to what extent does this game resonate with its nominal series? From the looks of it, it bears more of a likeness to the first titles, and to some extent FFIX and FFT. At a glance, it appears to have been modeled on the mainstream MMORPG fantasy genre. The return of the job class system and its potential for customization is a staple of the series, but the similarities end there, based on what I have gleaned from demo footage and screenshots. Granted, that's hardly conclusive.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> I think this is a fair statement. The fact is that like all FFs, Vana'diel is a unique world. One of the cool things about FFXI though is you do get cutscenes from taking on/completing quests, and I think there is a more immersing feel to it than your typical MMORPG. Square is supposed to also constantly keep the game storyline flowing with new areas, new quests, changing world events, etc.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Are there any familiar items or weapons<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> You will see a lot of familiar names, such as mithril bronze, and brass weapons. All weapons and armor have a minimum equipable level, and an of course you have your items that give   HP, MP, stats, elemental resistances, etc. As far as other special abilities, in the instance of weapons if you are talking about effects like elemental damage, or inflicting silence, then yes. You won't see stuff like clickies as you do in EQ. However, there is very high level armor that gives special abilities such as increased/decreased hate, reduced casting failures, or increased magic skills.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Are there degrees of spells (e.g. Fire, Fira, Firaga)? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> Yes, but they are old school as in Fire 1, Fire 2, Fire 3, etc. Once again many of these names will ring similar, blizzard, thunder, aero, water, stone, sleep, flare. White magic is similiar with Cure 1, 2, Protect 1, 2, Protectera 1, 2. For White magic, cure is for a single target, and curaga is for the party, stuff like that. Black magic, you have your standard spells and then your Group spells to attack groups of enemies.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Is it possible to cast summon spells (e.g. Bahamut, Shiva, Ifirit)? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> Oh definately, if you are a Summoner <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> . You will again notice many familiar names again, such as Ifrit, Shiva, and Leviathan, and also each summon gets stronger attacks based on your level.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>How many jobs are there really, as I have seen only a few mentioned on the official website?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Basic Jobs: Warrior, Monk, Thief, White Mage, Black Mage, Red Mage.<br>
<br>
Advanced Jobs: Paladin, Bard, Dark Knight, Beastmaster, Ranger, Summoner, Samurai, Ninja, Dragoon<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Can you learn special abilities from equipment, or is it level-based?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> Special abilities are strictly level based.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>How difficult is it to advance in level compared to the langorous crawl of EQ?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> Unfortunately you are not going to get a break here. If anything I would say leveling takes even more time than in EQ, but I don't find it to be quite as tedious. The combat system is one of the elements I enjoyed, and it is incredibly fun and addictive. Plus, since you will nearly always be fighting in groups for much better experience, not to mention how easy it is to find groups, it makes it a bit more enjoyable. Based on my experience, I think for a familiar player it would probably take about two weeks worth of constant 4-5 hours of leveling a day to get to 30. For someone who is completely new to the game and wasn't in beta, you are looking at a significantly longer amount of time. This does not include the fact that you will probably find yourself spending a great deal of time on quests and getting to know the world initially. I am sure nearly everyone will want to take time to do the subjob quest at level 18, and then proceeds to level up a second job, if they haven't prior to completing the quest. Not to mention if you want to unlock one of the special jobs you will need to be of appropriate level, and then do the quest needed to unlock it. Then of course you will be starting that job from level 1.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>How expensive are these World Passes required to play on the same server as a friend?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> The cost of a world pass varies by how many players there are on that particular server, and buying one in the Beta netted you 5 uses. I have heard that this might be reduced to 1 as the servers fill up. Initially, they will not be very expensive at all, around 100 to 150 Gil which not very hard at all to raise. However as more and more people begin to populate the server, the price of the pass will continue to increase. I have heard on some of the most populated servers, they go for around 1500 Gil. I guess this helps serve as a check and balance to keep server populations relatively equal.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Are chocobos costly, and can anyone ride them?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> Anyone can potentially ride them, but you first get your chocobo license by completing a quest. To do this you must be level 20 and you have to kill a certain enemy to get 4 or 5 of a particular grass item to feed the chocobo. Once you get your license you can then rent out a chocobo to ride, and they are relatively cheap, like around 100 gil. I also think the price goes down as you increase in level, though I don't quite remember.<br>
<br>
I will get into the battle mechanics a bit later, I am posting from work so time is of course a bit limited, but nonetheless as I said is unique and fun, and definitely one of the best parts about FFXI. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=samuraicowboy>Samurai Cowboy</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://studiocyen.net/blue/mini/comeon.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/22/03 11:19 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2026.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Re:</span><hr size=1> Thanks, Deldrach.  You have essentially cured my bewonderment.  I hadn't realized that the list of sub-jobs was that expansive.  The open-endedness of the job system is definitely a departure from the norm.  Also, it's heartening to hear that some of those endearing nuances of the series are returning.  <br>
