<br>
And yes...I think I'm going to do it...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:yellow;font-size:medium;">Deldrach's FFXI Job FAQ v 0.10</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>I.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> First off, there are three general rules for main/sub combinations.<br>
<br>
1. Race does matter. I hate to say it but in FFXI more so than EQ this is very true. The fact is in EQ it is not very hard to max your INT as a Wizard no matter what race you are, but if you are a high level Taru Taru Black Mage in FFXI with full artifact armor (best armor in the game at the moment), you will have a great deal more INT &amp; MP than a Black Mage of any other race. This cuts across the board with stats for other races/jobs. When other players are forming parties, if you are playing an uncommon race/job combo you will probably be passed over quite a bit, but such is life. However if you are a Hume, one of the advantages is that since you have pretty good all around stats you can switch jobs easily and still be effective, allowing for much more versatility. Keep this in mind in whether you plan on experimenting with a lot of different jobs, or specializing in just a certain one.<br>
<br>
2. Don't mix Melee and Magic! Yes, I know that Ninja/Summoner sounds pretty cool but it is just not going to be viable, and neither will that White Mage/Paladin. Just don't do it!<br>
<br>
3. Advanced Jobs generally do not make good sub Jobs. (With the exception of Samurai for most melees)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>II.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Now on to class explanations.<br>
<br>
1. Monk<br>
<br>
These guys make great damage dealers and have a good deal of hit points, but don't expect them to tank because they don't have much defense. I have heard that high level Monks are a great asset to groups, but they suffer from a midlevel funk and can be a bit tough to level.<br>
<br>
Preferred sub jobs: Warrior, Thief, Samurai<br>
<br>
2. Thief<br>
<br>
There are a lot of Thieves running around in Vana'deil, and for good reason. After level 30, Thieves get an ability that is essential for helping to control hate (aggro) in a party. They also are pretty good damage dealers as well, and are a great job/subjob for earning Gil. In fact, Thieves make great subjobs for nearly any melee class.<br>
<br>
Preferred Sub Jobs: Warrior, Monk, Ninja, Ranger<br>
<br>
3. Warrior<br>
<br>
For a melee class, Warriors are fairly well balanced and versatile. Depending on the sub job you chose, they can be either the second best tank in the game or can be a decent damage dealer as well. They can use a variety of weapons, but their preferred weapon is the 2-handed Axe, and their weapons skills provide good damage all around. Warrior also makes a very good sub job for any other melee job.<br>
<br>
Preferred Sub Jobs: Monk, Thief, Samurai<br>
<br>
4. Black Mage<br>
<br>
The Black Mage is there for one purpose, dishing out the pain. They are the second best damage dealer in the game and will often sub White Mage as well to act as a backup healer. Just watch your hate and don't get hit and you will be ok. Black Mages are always in high demand.<br>
<br>
Preferred Sub Jobs: White Mage, Red Mage, Summoner<br>
<br>
5. White Mage<br>
<br>
Well you probably don't need to ask what these guys do. These guys are there to heal party members and make sure everyone makes it through the day. WMs have a few support spells as well.<br>
<br>
Preferred Sub Jobs: Black Mage, Red Mage, Summoner, Bard<br>
<br>
6. Red Mage<br>
<br>
You hear the term jack of all trades used quite often to describe Red Mages, but I don't think that really sums up what they can do. First off nobody can enfeeble(debuff, slow, paralyze, Bio 2) like these guys can, and they are always very sought after for groups, particularly after level 41. At level 41 Red Mages receive what may well be one of the best abilities in the entire game, the spell Refresh, which is a spell that increases MP regeneration. In addition they have good attack spells, a fast cast ability, and can also serve as a primary healer in place of a White Mage. Their melee skills tend to die off after about level 20, but if you are a Red Mage, you probably will never have to look very far for a group.<br>
<br>
Preferred Sub Jobs: Black Mage, White Mage, Summoner, Bard<br>
<br>
7. Paladin<br>
<br>
In FFXI, Paladins=Meatshields, plain and simple. They are the best tank in the game...period. If you are a Paladin, you will be expected to sub Warrior for that job's taunt abilities. I have heard of a few Paladins that sub White Mage, and use Curaga to gain a great deal of enemy hate, but I cannot vouch for the effectiveness of this.<br>
<br>
Preferred Sub Jobs: Warrior<br>
<br>
8. Dark Knight<br>
<br>
These guys are the 3rd best damage dealers in the game. Think Rangers from EQ. They can really dish it out but they can't take much damage and would make horrible tanks for any foolish enough to try that. Based on my experience from the Beta, I think you are going to see a hell of a lot of these guys running around, and getting groups may be a bit tough because of this. They are known for using a Scythe, and their trademark weaponskill, Guillotine, is just plain awesome, and the damage from a high level Dark Knight subbing Samurai is a sight to behold. Managing hate however can be extremely tough, and so you will probably see a lot of these guys sub Thief to help in that department.<br>
<br>
Preferred Sub Jobs: Warrior, Thief, Samurai<br>
<br>
9. Summoner<br>
<br>
I must admit that my experience partying with Summoners was very limited, but the Summoner is not quite the job that people think it is. They serve more of a group support role than that of pure damage dealer, and their summons can't stay out for very long because they are huge MP hogs. With a Summoner in the group, a Bard or Red Mage becomes that much more vital for MP regeneration. If you want to deal damage, put on the funky BM hat instead.<br>
<br>
Preferred Sub Jobs: White Mage<br>
<br>
10. Bard<br>
<br>
Quick! What is the most sought after job when forming a party? No not a White Mage, it's a Bard. Now what will be the rarest job to find in FFXI? Yes, you guessed it, Bards. I am not going to go as far in saying that Bards are required for high level groups, but it's pretty damn close. Their songs provide a whole array of enfeeblements and stat enhancements, in addition to being great healers with a bit of damage dealing thrown in as well. Want mana regeneration? Get a bard to sing Ballad. In addition Bard Songs don't use up any MP. It is almost beyond belief how much more effective Mages can be when there is a Bard present.<br>
<br>
Preferred Sub Jobs: White Mage<br>
<br>
11. Beast Tamer<br>
<br>
This was the only class I did not have the opportunity to group with in the Beta. There are tales told of their great soloing ability by taming a monster and then using it to attack another, which is similiar to charming in EQ. I am not sure how well they can function in a group, but I know that just encountering one in Beta was pretty rare, and I don't expect many people will choose this job.<br>
<br>
Preferred Sub Jobs: Warrior, White Mage<br>
<br>
12. Ninja<br>
<br>
These guys are well known for their ability to dual wield. They do pretty decent damage, and I have heard as tanks if you really burn Gil on equipment and their Ninjitsu skills that their tanking ability rivals that of even Paladins. However, this is very costly as their skills require Gil to use and so this can be a very expensive job if you want to get the most out of it.<br>
<br>
Preferred Sub Jobs: Warrior, Thief, Samurai<br>
<br>
13. Ranger<br>
<br>
Bar none the Ranger is potentially the king of damage in FFXI. I say potentially because like Ninjas they are very expensive. In fact they are the most costly job in the game, because they must pay an arm &amp; leg for ammo, namely bullets or arrows. If you are a Ranger you can expect to be poor. Rangers of course use bows and guns to attack from a distance and their Scan ability is similar to track in EQ. I'm sure a lot of Rangers will probably sub Thief to help out in the money-making department.<br>
<br>
Preferred Sub Jobs: Warrior, Thief, Ninja, Samurai<br>
<br>
14. Samurai<br>
<br>
The Samurai is the key to chaining weapon skills which allows for the party to dish out a huge amount of damage. I expect a lot of party leaders will be Samurais for this reason. Their own damage dealing abilities are so-so, and they have about average statistics, but in combat you can expect to be very active in starting up skill chains. The Samurai is probably the only advanced class that can be subbed effectively as well for this reason, though since their Concentration ability(which charges TP and allows for quick use of weapon skills) isn't gained until level 30, this job only becomes popular as a sub job at very high level, 60 .<br>
<br>
Preferred Sub Jobs: Warrior, Monk, Thief<br>
<br>
15. Dragoon<br>
<br>
Grrr.....I want to like this class, I really do. Dragoons were after all one of the really cool elements from the FF series. However, in FFXI from my perspective they are a huge disappointment. Their defining ability is not their various jumps (most of which suck), but their pet Wyvern. Yes Dragoons are primarily a pet class. If it dies, they will be gimped for quite some time until they are able to summon another one, and I believe that ability has a 2 hour refresh timer. Even with the Wvyern I was never overly impressed with their damage capability, though it does get a cool breath weapon depending on the Dragoon's subjob. You do get to name it as well which I guess is a plus. There were a lot of people that did the quest for Dragoon in beta, and sadly I expect a lot of people will be choosing this job simply because it's a &quot;Dragoon&quot;. Finding a party may become very difficult, but who knows I could be wrong.<br>
<br>
Preferred Sub Jobs: Warrior, Thief, White Mage, Samurai <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=deldrach>Deldrach</A> at: 10/27/03 7:44 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=orlafv>OrlaFV</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/27/03 8:16 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2026.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Final Fantasy XI</span><hr size=1> Okay ... not sure I understand the whole server thing completely, could you explain for me?  (call me stupid!)<br>
